-- Taiwan's September Consumer Prices Climb on Higher Clothing, Housing Costs
-- B y   C h i n m e i   S u n g   a n d   A d e l a   L i n
-- 2010-10-05T08:38:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-05/taiwan-s-consumer-prices-increase-0-29-in-september-from-year-earlier.html
Taiwan’s  consumer prices  rose in
September as clothing and electricity costs increased.  The consumer price index advanced by 0.29 percent in
September from a year earlier, the statistics bureau said today
in Taipei. That compared with the median  estimate  for a 0.4
percent increase in a Bloomberg News survey of 13 economists.
Prices fell a revised 0.47 percent in August.  Taiwan’s central bank last week raised the island’s
benchmark interest rate for the second time this year to 1.5
percent, and said it will try to prevent real-estate speculation.
Governor  Perng Fai-nan  told reporters that inflation this year
may be lower than the 1.23 percent forecast by the statistics
bureau in August.  “The economy is growing rapidly, and despite sluggish
wages, some upward price pressure could be emerging from the
demand side,”  Tine Olsen , an economist at Moody’s economy.com
in Sydney, said ahead of today’s announcement.  Taiwan’s central bank unexpectedly raised the benchmark
rate by 0.125 percentage point in June from a record-low 1.25
percent. In the same board meeting, it also ordered a 70 percent
cap on loans for second homes in the Taipei metropolitan area
and canceled grace periods on principal repayments to curb
speculation. Perng last week urged “proper rules” for loans
using vacant land as collateral, saying he will use “moral
suasion” to try and prevent credit being extended to
speculators.  Stocks, Currency  Full-year inflation will be 1.23 percent, down from May’s
projection of 1.4 percent, Taiwan’s statistics bureau said Aug.
19, while also raising the island’s economic growth forecast to
8.24 percent from 6.14 percent.  The report was released after the close of trading on the
stock exchange. The Taiex index fell 0.6 percent. The Taiwan
dollar rose 0.01 percent to NT$31.252 at the 4 p.m. close local
time, according to Taipei Forex Inc.  Food prices fell 2.03 percent from a year earlier, because
they were compared against high levels in September 2009,
today’s report showed. The price of transportation advanced 0.84
percent and clothing prices climbed 3.83 percent. Housing costs
gained 1.59 percent, with electricity rising 13.55 percent.  Core consumer prices , a category excluding vegetables,
fruit, fish and energy, climbed 0.71 percent after increasing a
revised 0.38 percent in August.  Wholesale prices, which track the cost of goods sold to
retailers and producers, rose 3.64 percent from a year earlier,
compared with a revised gain of 3.35 percent in August.  To contact the reporter on this story:
